# Business-term import fixtures (#1754) reproduce real exports from commercial Business Glossary tools
# byte-for-byte, INCLUDING their original CRLF line endings (Alation/Atlan/Dataplex/IBM/Purview are
# Windows-tool exports) and trailing empty columns. That fidelity is the point of
# BusinessTermImportFileParserCommercialExportTest — it proves the parser handles messy real-world
# exports, so the whitespace must NOT be "cleaned up".
#
#   -text                        -> Git never normalizes their line endings, so the CRLF / trailing-column
#                                   parser coverage cannot be silently dropped on checkout/commit.
#   whitespace=-trailing-space   -> `git diff --check` does not flag the intentional trailing whitespace
#                                   (the CR of CRLF and the trailing empty column), while the files stay
#                                   textually diffable.
*.csv  -text whitespace=-trailing-space
*.tsv  -text whitespace=-trailing-space
# XLSX fixtures are ZIP binaries.
*.xlsx binary
